and geographical data, highlighting the multifaceted nature of GAD.\n\n## Generalized Anxiety Disorder as the central entity\n\nGeneralized Anxiety Disorder (GAD) is the central entity in this community, characterized by persistent and excessive worry. This condition significantly impacts individuals' quality of life due to its chronic nature and pervasive sense of unease. GAD is linked to various symptoms and research studies, making it a focal point for understanding the community's dynamics. [Data: Entities (14), Relationships (25, 63, 64)]\n\n## Noyes' research on familial aggregation of GAD\n\nNoyes is a key entity in this community, having reported on the familial aggregation of GAD in 1987. This research highlights the genetic and familial aspects of GAD, contributing to a deeper understanding of its etiology and prevalence. Noyes' work is crucial in the context of GAD research and its implications for treatment and prevention. [Data: Entities (16), Relationships (16)]\n\n## Zhejiang's role in GAD prevalence data\n\nZhejiang is significant in this community due to a survey conducted in 2001 that provided data on the prevalence of GAD. This geographical data is essential for understanding the distribution and impact of GAD in specific regions, aiding in targeted interventions and resource allocation. [Data: Entities (25), Relationships (25)]\n\n## Free-floating anxiety as a key symptom of GAD\n\nFree-floating anxiety is a key symptom of GAD, characterized by a pervasive sense of unease without a specific cause. This symptom is crucial for diagnosing and understanding the nature of GAD, as it differentiates GAD from other anxiety disorders. The relationship between GAD and free-floating anxiety underscores the complexity of the disorder. [Data: Entities (68), Relationships (63)]\n\n## Apprehensive expectation as a core symptom of GAD\n\nApprehensive expectation is a core symptom of GAD, where the patient's worry is disproportionate to the actual situation. This